&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is -1 and +1.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;The value of the coefficient of correlation &amp;#39;r&amp;#39; lies between -1 and 1.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If &amp;#39;r&amp;#39; is closer to 1, it indicates a strong positive correlation, meaning that as one variable increases, the other variable tends to increase.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If &amp;#39;r&amp;#39; is closer to -1, it indicates a strong negative correlation, meaning that as one variable increases, the other variable tends to decrease.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If &amp;#39;r&amp;#39; is close to 0, it suggests a weak or no linear correlation between the variables.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;So, the range for the coefficient of correlation &amp;#39;r&amp;#39; is -1 to 1, inclusive.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;user-select: initial !important;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Given: &lt;/strong&gt;The correlation coefficient between x and y is r.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Concept:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correlation coefficient measures the strength and direction of the linear relationship between two variables.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Calculation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The transformation of y involves multiplication by -3. Multiplying one of the variables by a negative value changes the direction of the correlation.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;= - r&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hence, the correlation coefficient between ( 3x + 4 ) and ( -3y + 3 ) is&amp;nbsp; - r&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;lt; 1&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The product of the regression coefficients of Y on X (b&lt;sub&gt;yx&lt;/sub&gt;) and X on Y (b&lt;sub&gt;xy&lt;/sub&gt;) is equal to the ratio of variances of X and Y.&lt;br /&gt;
&amp;rArr;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\( b_{yx} \times b_{xy} = \frac{σ_x²}{σ_y²}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Assuming that the variances &amp;sigma;&lt;sub&gt;x&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;sup&gt;&amp;sup2;&lt;/sup&gt; and &amp;sigma;&lt;sub&gt;y&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;sup&gt;&amp;sup2;&lt;/sup&gt; are positive (since variance can&amp;#39;t be negative), then if b&lt;sub&gt;xy&lt;/sub&gt; &amp;gt; 1, it must be the case that b&lt;sub&gt;yx&lt;/sub&gt; &amp;lt; 1.&lt;br /&gt;
This is because if b&lt;sub&gt;xy&lt;/sub&gt; &amp;gt; 1, then in order for their product to be a positive number less than or equal to 1 (Since,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(\frac{σ_x²}{σ_y²}\)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;can&amp;#39;t be greater than 1 unless the variance of X is greater than that of Y), b&lt;sub&gt;yx&lt;/sub&gt; must be less than 1.&amp;nbsp;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Hence, if b&lt;sub&gt;xy&lt;/sub&gt; &amp;gt; 1, then indeed b&lt;sub&gt;yx&lt;/sub&gt; &amp;lt; 1.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;This property is known as the Magnitude property.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;0.7&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correlation coefficient, denoted by r, quantifies the linear relationship between two random variables. It is formally defined as the covariance between the two variables divided by the product of their standard deviations.&amp;nbsp;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(r = {Cov(X, Y) \over σ_X σ_Y}\)&lt;/span&gt;; where,&amp;nbsp;Cov(X, Y) denotes the covariance between X and Y, &amp;sigma;&lt;sub&gt;X&lt;/sub&gt; denotes the standard deviation of X, and &amp;sigma;&lt;sub&gt;Y&lt;/sub&gt; denotes the standard deviation of Y.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Let&amp;#39;s denote the correlation between X and Y as r&lt;sub&gt;XY&lt;/sub&gt;.&amp;nbsp;Therefore,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(r_{XY} = {Cov(X, Y) \over σ_X σ_Y}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Now, considering the transformations U = X - 5 and V = Y + 2, we need to find the correlation coefficient between U and V, denoted by&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(r_{UV}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Given the properties of covariance and variance under linear transformation, we have:&lt;br /&gt;
Cov(U, V) = Cov(X - 5, Y + 2) = Cov(X, Y)&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&amp;sigma;&lt;sub&gt;U&lt;/sub&gt; = &amp;sigma;&lt;sub&gt;X &lt;/sub&gt;(since the variance and hence the standard deviation do not change with shifts)&lt;br /&gt;
&amp;sigma;&lt;sub&gt;V&lt;/sub&gt; = &amp;sigma;&lt;sub&gt;Y&lt;/sub&gt; (since the variance and hence the standard deviation do not change with shifts)&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Then, substituting these into the formula for r&lt;sub&gt;UV&lt;/sub&gt;, we have:&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(r_{UV} = {Cov(U, V)\over σ_U σ_V} = {Cov(X, Y) \over σ_X σ_Y} = r_{XY}\)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
In conclusion, a linear transformation that consists of adding or subtracting a constant from a random variable does not affect the correlation coefficient between two variables. Thus, if the correlation coefficient between X and Y is 0.7, the correlation coefficient between U = X - 5 and V = Y + 2 remains 0.7.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is 0.97.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;The coefficient of correlation, often denoted as &amp;quot;r,&amp;quot; measures the strength and direction of the linear relationship between two variables. It ranges between -1 and 1.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;To determine the coefficient of correlation from the given regression coefficients, we need to consider the relationship between the regression coefficients and the coefficient of correlation. Specifically, the coefficient of correlation is the square root of the product of the two regression coefficients:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Coefficient of Correlation (r) = &amp;radic;(Regression Coefficient 1 * Regression Coefficient 2)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Given that the regression coefficients are 0.8 and 1.2:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Coefficient of Correlation (r) = &amp;radic;(0.8 * 1.2)&lt;br /&gt;
Coefficient of Correlation (r) = &amp;radic;0.96&lt;br /&gt;
Coefficient of Correlation (r) &amp;asymp; 0.97&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Therefore, the value of the coefficient of correlation is approximately 0.97.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
